Some apparent taint of insanity seems to come in, completing and partly explaining the whole: perhaps traceable sometimes in the clear evidence of public documents 3 as in the attempt, in his published auto- biography, to explain the condemnation of Seianus by a falsehood of childish transparency 10; or in the famous words preserved of his letter to the senate, publishing to the world his agony of soul ¹¹. Again, at one time-reproach seems to lacerate him ¹², at another he parades it¹³; he hovers round and round Rome and never enters it 1’; shifts his place restlessly in the last stage of decrepitude ¹⁵.
